^-|fp||ht|l|VA|5|AT|^c@2^Z@3A. Bidding over a 1NT overcall is different than any other auction. Over suit overcalls doubles are negative and new suits are forcing. But over 1NT the opposite is true. Double shows a good hand (9+) and new suits are to play. Sort of the same idea of how you bid after an opponent's takeout double (e.g. you redouble with a good hand and new suits are not forcing).

B. I know a man whose wife will not let him play bridge. He, therefore, takes long lunches from his tax business in order to play. But this means no one can call him at home for a date to play. So he used to show up regularly on Friday afternoons at the Northern Virginia sectional tournaments without a partner. And he would fill in with anyone around (usually terrible players no one else wanted as partner) either in the Men's Pairs, or even the Women's Pairs, if the movement had a half a table. To make a long story short, Rob won the Northern Virginia women's Pairs three times. The last time, one gal got so mad, she persuaded the Northern Virginia Board to bar him from further Women's Pairs.

I said to him, "Rob, it's not that easy to win the Women's Pairs, particularly with the pick-up partners you had! How in the world did you do it?"

"Well," he said, "I just filled in at the last minute and there was no time to talk about conventions or make out a full convention card. So each time we just wrote at the top: NO ONE PLAYS BELOW 2NT." See that?|
