^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|I had some questions about DONT and CAPP which I will answer first. The reason I strongly prefer DONT is that it lets you effectively describe both 1 suited and 2 suited hands and compete at the 2 level. In general, once someone opens a strong NT, the odds that your side has game is small. So playing a convention that lets you plays partials at the 2 level is a good thing. And DONT is the only convention that does that. |
PG| ***** 49 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|The problem with CAPP is that on many hands you end up having to go to the 3 level. For example, if you have a major and a minor, you bid the major and then if partner has to correct to the minor, you are at the 3 level. |
PG| ***** 50 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Also, some argue DONT does not allow you to play penalty doubles. However, I challenge you to find a hand in the next year where someone opens a strong 1N and you get a good result by doubling them at 1N. They will either make it or run out to a suit. So a convention that allows you to double 1NT for penalty is really not very useful IMO even against weak NT.|
PG| ***** 51 ***** |


NT|^B@2
